1
00:00:01,580 --> 00:00:05,445
To finish out the reinforcement
learning formalism,

2
00:00:05,445 --> 00:00:07,560
instead of looking
at something as

3
00:00:07,560 --> 00:00:10,650
complicated as a
helicopter or a robot dog,

4
00:00:10,650 --> 00:00:13,980
we can use a simplified example

5
00:00:13,980 --> 00:00:17,085
that's loosely inspired
by the Mars rover.

6
00:00:17,085 --> 00:00:18,390
This is adapted from

7
00:00:18,390 --> 00:00:20,265
the example due to
Stanford professor

8
00:00:20,265 --> 00:00:21,990
Emma Branskill and one of

9
00:00:21,990 --> 00:00:24,600
my collaborators,
Jagriti Agrawal,

10
00:00:24,600 --> 00:00:26,580
who had actually
written code that

11
00:00:26,580 --> 00:00:28,605
is actually controlling
the Mars rover

12
00:00:28,605 --> 00:00:30,510
right now that also helped me

13
00:00:30,510 --> 00:00:32,820
talk through and helped
develop this example.

14
00:00:32,820 --> 00:00:37,020
Let's take a look. We'll
develop reinforcement learning

15
00:00:37,020 --> 00:00:43,110
using a simplified example
inspired by the Mars rover.

16
00:00:43,110 --> 00:00:45,830
In this application,
the rover can

17
00:00:45,830 --> 00:00:48,680
be in any of six positions,

18
00:00:48,680 --> 00:00:51,355
as shown by the six boxes here.

19
00:00:51,355 --> 00:00:53,960
The rover, it might
start off, say,

20
00:00:53,960 --> 00:00:58,355
in disposition into
fourth box shown here.

21
00:00:58,355 --> 00:01:00,830
The position of
the Mars rover is

22
00:01:00,830 --> 00:01:03,930
called the state in
reinforcement learning,

23
00:01:03,930 --> 00:01:06,395
and I'm going to call
these six states,

24
00:01:06,395 --> 00:01:08,330
state 1, state 2,

25
00:01:08,330 --> 00:01:10,025
state 3, state 4,

26
00:01:10,025 --> 00:01:12,200
state 5, and state 6,

27
00:01:12,200 --> 00:01:15,730
and so the rover is
starting off in state 4.

28
00:01:15,730 --> 00:01:18,710
Now the rover was
sent to Mars to

29
00:01:18,710 --> 00:01:21,725
try to carry out different
science missions.

30
00:01:21,725 --> 00:01:24,380
It can go to different places to

31
00:01:24,380 --> 00:01:27,660
use its sensors such as
a drill, or a radar,

32
00:01:27,660 --> 00:01:29,525
or a spectrometer to

33
00:01:29,525 --> 00:01:32,540
analyze the rock at different
places on the planet,

34
00:01:32,540 --> 00:01:34,250
or go to different
places to take

35
00:01:34,250 --> 00:01:36,865
interesting pictures for
scientists on earth to look at.

36
00:01:36,865 --> 00:01:40,235
In this example, state
1 here on the left has

37
00:01:40,235 --> 00:01:42,380
a very interesting surface that

38
00:01:42,380 --> 00:01:45,400
scientists would love
for the rover to sample.

39
00:01:45,400 --> 00:01:47,045
State 6 also has

40
00:01:47,045 --> 00:01:49,220
a pretty interesting
surface that

41
00:01:49,220 --> 00:01:51,935
scientists would quite
like the rover to sample,

42
00:01:51,935 --> 00:01:54,215
but not as interesting
as state 1.

43
00:01:54,215 --> 00:01:57,770
We would more
likely to carry out

44
00:01:57,770 --> 00:02:01,685
the science mission ant
state 1 than at state 6,

45
00:02:01,685 --> 00:02:03,995
but state 1 is further away.

46
00:02:03,995 --> 00:02:07,280
The way we will
reflect state 1 being

47
00:02:07,280 --> 00:02:11,320
potentially more valuable is
through the reward function.

48
00:02:11,320 --> 00:02:15,765
The reward at state 1 is a 100,

49
00:02:15,765 --> 00:02:19,620
and the reward at stage 6 is 40,

50
00:02:19,620 --> 00:02:22,965
and the rewards at all of
the other states in-between,

51
00:02:22,965 --> 00:02:26,450
I'm going to write as a reward
of zero because there's

52
00:02:26,450 --> 00:02:28,340
not as much
interesting science to

53
00:02:28,340 --> 00:02:30,440
be done at these states 2,

54
00:02:30,440 --> 00:02:31,955
3, 4, and 5.

55
00:02:31,955 --> 00:02:34,430
On each step, the rover gets

56
00:02:34,430 --> 00:02:36,785
to choose one of two actions.

57
00:02:36,785 --> 00:02:42,695
It can either go to the left
or it can go to the right.

58
00:02:42,695 --> 00:02:46,075
The question is, what
should the rover do?

59
00:02:46,075 --> 00:02:47,930
In reinforcement
learning, we pay

60
00:02:47,930 --> 00:02:49,700
a lot of attention
to the rewards

61
00:02:49,700 --> 00:02:51,380
because that's how we know if

62
00:02:51,380 --> 00:02:54,515
the robot is doing
well or poorly.

63
00:02:54,515 --> 00:02:57,200
Let's look at some
examples of what might

64
00:02:57,200 --> 00:02:59,835
happen if the robot
was to go left,

65
00:02:59,835 --> 00:03:01,425
starting from state 4.

66
00:03:01,425 --> 00:03:05,265
Then initially
starting from state 4,

67
00:03:05,265 --> 00:03:07,590
it will receive a
reward of zero,

68
00:03:07,590 --> 00:03:09,525
and after going left,

69
00:03:09,525 --> 00:03:10,815
it gets to state 3,

70
00:03:10,815 --> 00:03:13,425
where it receives again
a reward of zero.

71
00:03:13,425 --> 00:03:15,225
Then it gets to state 2,

72
00:03:15,225 --> 00:03:16,920
receives the reward is 0,

73
00:03:16,920 --> 00:03:18,755
and finally just to state 1,

74
00:03:18,755 --> 00:03:21,875
where it receives
a reward of 100.

75
00:03:21,875 --> 00:03:24,680
For this application,
I'm going to assume that

76
00:03:24,680 --> 00:03:27,605
when it gets either
state 1 or state 6,

77
00:03:27,605 --> 00:03:29,540
that the day ends.

78
00:03:29,540 --> 00:03:32,255
In reinforcement learning,
we sometimes call this

79
00:03:32,255 --> 00:03:35,160
a terminal state,

80
00:03:35,160 --> 00:03:37,030
and what that means is that,

81
00:03:37,030 --> 00:03:39,665
after it gets to one of
these terminals states,

82
00:03:39,665 --> 00:03:41,315
gets a reward at that state,

83
00:03:41,315 --> 00:03:43,595
but then nothing
happens after that.

84
00:03:43,595 --> 00:03:45,320
Maybe the robots run out of

85
00:03:45,320 --> 00:03:47,225
fuel or ran out of
time for the day,

86
00:03:47,225 --> 00:03:50,330
which is why it only
gets to either enjoy

87
00:03:50,330 --> 00:03:54,225
the 100 or the 40 reward,

88
00:03:54,225 --> 00:03:56,370
but then that's it for the day.

89
00:03:56,370 --> 00:03:59,225
It doesn't get to earn
additional rewards after that.

90
00:03:59,225 --> 00:04:01,595
Now instead of going left,

91
00:04:01,595 --> 00:04:04,415
the robot could also
choose to go to the right,

92
00:04:04,415 --> 00:04:06,320
in which case from state 4,

93
00:04:06,320 --> 00:04:10,755
it would first have
a reward of zero,

94
00:04:10,755 --> 00:04:13,335
and then it'll move right
and get to state 5,

95
00:04:13,335 --> 00:04:15,435
have another reward of zero,

96
00:04:15,435 --> 00:04:17,030
and then it will get to this

97
00:04:17,030 --> 00:04:18,800
other terminal
state on the right,

98
00:04:18,800 --> 00:04:21,625
state 6 and get a reward of 40.

99
00:04:21,625 --> 00:04:26,395
But going left and going
right are the only options.

100
00:04:26,395 --> 00:04:29,230
One thing the robot could
do is it can start from

101
00:04:29,230 --> 00:04:32,885
state 4 and decide to
move to the right.

102
00:04:32,885 --> 00:04:35,270
It goes from state 4-5,

103
00:04:35,270 --> 00:04:37,010
gets a reward of zero in state

104
00:04:37,010 --> 00:04:38,885
4 and a reward of
zero in state 5,

105
00:04:38,885 --> 00:04:41,990
and then maybe it changes its
mind and decides to start

106
00:04:41,990 --> 00:04:45,380
going to the left as
follows, in which case,

107
00:04:45,380 --> 00:04:48,760
it will get a reward of zero
at state 4, at state 3,

108
00:04:48,760 --> 00:04:50,450
at state 2, and then the reward

109
00:04:50,450 --> 00:04:53,170
of 100 when it gets to state 1.

110
00:04:53,170 --> 00:04:56,730
In this sequence of
actions and states,

111
00:04:56,730 --> 00:04:58,790
the robot is wasting
better time.

112
00:04:58,790 --> 00:05:02,090
So this maybe isn't such a
great way to take actions,

113
00:05:02,090 --> 00:05:04,865
but it is one choice that
the algorithm could pick,

114
00:05:04,865 --> 00:05:07,205
but hopefully you
won't pick this one.

115
00:05:07,205 --> 00:05:10,820
To summarize, at
every time step,

116
00:05:10,820 --> 00:05:13,280
the robot is in some state,

117
00:05:13,280 --> 00:05:15,530
which I'll call S,

118
00:05:15,530 --> 00:05:19,285
and it gets to choose an action,

119
00:05:19,285 --> 00:05:23,330
and it also enjoys some rewards,

120
00:05:23,330 --> 00:05:26,570
R of S that it gets
from that state.

121
00:05:26,570 --> 00:05:28,550
As a result of this action,

122
00:05:28,550 --> 00:05:32,165
it to some new state S prime.

123
00:05:32,165 --> 00:05:33,890
As a concrete example,

124
00:05:33,890 --> 00:05:37,910
when the robot was in state
4 and it took the action,

125
00:05:37,910 --> 00:05:43,110
go left, maybe didn't
enjoy the reward of

126
00:05:43,110 --> 00:05:45,240
zero associated with that state

127
00:05:45,240 --> 00:05:49,290
4 and it won't have
any new state 3.

128
00:05:49,290 --> 00:05:50,480
When you learn about

129
00:05:50,480 --> 00:05:52,669
specific reinforcement
learning algorithms,

130
00:05:52,669 --> 00:05:55,325
you see that these four things,

131
00:05:55,325 --> 00:05:58,190
the state, action, the
reward and next state,

132
00:05:58,190 --> 00:05:59,960
which is what happens
basically every

133
00:05:59,960 --> 00:06:01,700
time you take an
action that just

134
00:06:01,700 --> 00:06:03,020
be a core elements of

135
00:06:03,020 --> 00:06:04,940
what reinforcement
learning algorithms will

136
00:06:04,940 --> 00:06:08,805
look at when deciding
how to take actions.

137
00:06:08,805 --> 00:06:12,170
Just for clarity,
the reward here,

138
00:06:12,170 --> 00:06:16,055
R of S, this is the reward
associated with this state.

139
00:06:16,055 --> 00:06:18,380
This reward of
zero is associated

140
00:06:18,380 --> 00:06:21,595
with state 4 rather
than with state 3.

141
00:06:21,595 --> 00:06:24,125
That's the formalism of how

142
00:06:24,125 --> 00:06:26,990
a reinforcement learning
application works.

143
00:06:26,990 --> 00:06:28,010
In the next video,

144
00:06:28,010 --> 00:06:30,260
let's take a look
at how we specify

145
00:06:30,260 --> 00:06:31,935
exactly what we want

146
00:06:31,935 --> 00:06:33,770
the reinforcement
learning algorithm to do.

147
00:06:33,770 --> 00:06:36,290
In particular, we'll talk
about an important idea in

148
00:06:36,290 --> 00:06:38,870
reinforcement learning
called the return.

149
00:06:38,870 --> 00:06:42,360
Let's go on to the next video
